Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament has today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Penal Code, which condemns the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the exclusion of the minister, but the parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison by the alleged signing of an agreement with the disadvantaged Russia for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not firm yet, the court of appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there have been doubts about the fairness of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code, which condemned the former prime minister, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
For its approval, 226 votes were required.
