How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
The Czech tourists therefore went from vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at those times, but one had to put on the queue with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have (well known) in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The call - a promise of change - which was the condition for trips to the West, was not granted to the - politically unreliable agent - which thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their vacation in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs have been travelling has been a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the present favorite destination Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed to travel to the neighbouring States of Western Europe, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see them fed up on the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups in the parks were sleeping in tents, since our income from that time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take the food with you (conservations, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it the average wages, which about 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increased demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare travel using charter flight connections, which incredibly lowered travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volume.
At the end of the 90th century, Czechs were already travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have made countries distant and warm. This winter will already fly directly from Chequia to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3 per cent) and for the first time in their history, have spent on trips abroad over 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses on the stay site.
