While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: he had spent most of the time preceding his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After this summer's tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to get on Facebook.
\"We realized it wasn't that difficult to reach them,\" says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the DEMOS British Center of Studies.
Facebook's personal information ring is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way vendors have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing group fans all over Europe and then sent them advertisements, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
\"It's a totally new way to do an investigation,\" says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry at immigration.
However, in a kind of spin, those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen.
DEMOS's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the -I like - messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook’s “supernova of data” is generating a rise in research, boosting the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach with a folder on the street.
\"Before, when you were trying to poll people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.\"
\"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access,\" says Bartlett.
\"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly\"
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno, University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who spoke about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly greater risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent about the subject.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as residential counsellors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishes too many state updates with their drunks.
\"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it,\" said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Children's Health, Behavior and Development Center at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed”
Facebook is also constantly - blinking - to its own population to obtain data.
The Site Data Team has developed statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and an index of National Happiness (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom advocates long ago hold that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
