As a bassist, what are his influences?
That's so many.
Among the first things that happen to me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many who could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge relevant despite not being a fashion anymore?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's something wonderful because it's music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are doing now better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and has now become more positive.
What is the result of this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, such as The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a little positive.
