MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gen
Direct Social Security an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the type of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Childhood Obesity and Adolescence' protocol, which will allow for overweight associated markers.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Specialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the participation of the population whether or not it is right-wing, to visit the IMSS participating sports units in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Ponient Mexico State) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the objective of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the 14th of November on the World Diabetes Day, he stated that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and heredofamily history of disease, with the aim of avoiding risk factors that trigger such diseases as diabetes or renal failure.
It was detailed that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming increase in weight in children.
'Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years there was an increase in the case of children, 77 per cent in obesity, and girls 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', noted IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for searching for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexican has 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the comprehensive evaluation of children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (cantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, who are explained by each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle that they must make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic ailments: sedentaryness, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay for the most part of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid slums
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mix with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 thousand basins each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, he warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintaining an asphalt floor is appropriate, the basins could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the basins, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and thus the formation of basins.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, it added.
The above means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve the asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting vehicles and making efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it was a modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, it abounded, one last layer is placed called the rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. an arena that also bathes in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the treadmill also requires the appropriate thickness and the material of what is made must be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is moistened, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to leave, this causes a reblazing of all layers of the floor and thus the formation of basins.
In the process of forming a basin, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Investigators System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of basins and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the floor should always be related to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to avoid the formation of basins frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow to repair the basins easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
