In 2000, he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of the hands and feet.
The week of operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar was warned to wear minimum clothing for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he should identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was heading for the world's oldest guerrilla, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's decactile card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the corpse was located he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, transplanter, and flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was \"Alfonso Cano\"
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that it was the chief of the Farc.
