The North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which communicates directly Western Europe with Russia passing through the Baltic Sea fund, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have together turned the wheel of the valve controlling the Russian gas input into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, there will be an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas in Western Europe each year through a first of 1,224 km that communicate the St Petersburg region with the Mecklemburg-Pomerania Land.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the in-time completion of this enormous work presents the airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, North Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to shut down access to the markets in Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream as a - a new German-Soviet pact - with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,” confirmed François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against the anchorages of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
“It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” says Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream society.
It was also necessary to extend measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
There was provision for a water control platform in Sweden, but the project leaders gave up the same, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently on the sea off its coast.
“In case of failure, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute,” Jens Müller says.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released to the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to the forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a vessel, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full travel days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which has 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favourable.
Later, Gazprom rented the company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually being transported,” Jens Müller says.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30 per cent with the input of the shareholders and by 70 per cent with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Some valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
