Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
Around 19 per cent of disabled persons are seeking employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a well-established public policy, since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disappointment?
“No” says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the partnership that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
\"However, there is still a lot to be done.\"
It should be mentioned that disabled people continue to face numerous obstacles to access employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent of them have not completed bachelor's degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent for the average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and which - they constitute the quid of the problem - points out Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, a partnership created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those that are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Enterprise for the City noted that the directors surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disabilities, with an excessive representation of people on wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far away from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, which was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008 they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments - subject to this contribution - as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated a great deal of pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
\"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among large groups\"
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies with between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities, compared to 82 per cent of the companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
